These are undeniable examples of bad interpolation. They are the meddling of a scholar (of a kind), and they bring into sus- picion the authenticity of a good many of Ven.'s correct lections. They make it not unlikely that such readings as Ι. 718 diductas, 11. 29 solantemque‚ ΙΙ. 110 infidas, III. 641 reget, &c., mentioned above, may be no more than conjectural restorations. I have little doubt that we must refer to conjecture some other readings of Ven. which are in themselves perhaps unobjectionable, such as Ι. 433 contorquens for conuoluens, Ι. 800 regna for signa, III. 4 in- dictos for indtgnos, IV. 518 tempora for sidera, IV. 841 qua for quo, V. 23 necans for negans, V. 469 facies for species, V. 477 curasque for c(l2)arusque.
